International Tributes to the History of Flight
First Commercial SST Flight
The supersonic transport (SST) Tupolev TU-144,
named for designer Andrei Nikolaevich Tupolev, was
first unveiled by the Soviets at the 1965 Paris Air Show.
It underwent extensive testing between 1968 and 1975.
Then, on December 26, 1975, the plane officially
ushered in the era of supersonic transport. A sleek
Tupolev TU-144 loaded with cargo stood poised on
the runway in Moscow, waiting for take-off. The flight
would institute twice-weekly cargo service between
the Soviet capital and Alma Ata, near the China bor-
der. It was over almost as soon as it began, since the
plane covered the distance of nearly 2,000 miles at a
cruising speed of Mach 2.35.
The full-color cachet shows the Tupolev TU-144
streaking across the U.S.S.R. countryside on its his-
toric first commercial flight. The needle-nosed SST
had a wingspan of 94.5 feet and was powered by four
Kuznetsov 44,090-thrust turbofan engines.
Mint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued
by the Soviet Union in 1969. It pictures the nearly 216-
ft. long TU-144 streaking through the sky on its first
test flight at supersonic speed, in 1969.
Postmark: This Cover was postmarked in Moscow,
U.S.S.R. on December 26, 1985, the exact anniversary
of the first commercial SST flight.
